thread.title: Sault Elks Invitational cross country

author: Staff reports
title: Sault Elks Invitational cross country
text: Sault Elks Invitational cross country Comment Sault Ste. Marie Evening News - Sault Ste. Marie, MI By Staff reports Posted Oct. 12, 2015 at 7:57 PM By Staff reports Posted Oct. 12, 2015 at 7:57 PM SAULT STE. MARIE â€” Harbor Springs led the field in both the boys and girls meets at the 19th annual Sault Elks Invitational Saturday at the William Lynn Trails. Harbor Springs was the top overall boys team and won the Small School meet title with 29 points. The Sault boys were second overall and won the large school meet title with 44. Munising compiled 118 and won the Class D team scoring, while Cedarville had 133, Newberry 139, Ojibwe 175, Pickford 180, Manistique 200 and Brimley 214. The Sault boys placed four runners in the top nine. Aaron Kinsella, Isaac Corbiere and Chris Larson placed fifth-through-seventh in 18:03, 18:08 and 18:13, respectively. Andy Farlow was 9th (18:18) and Ryan Sanderson 17th (18:47). Mikael Ranta also cracked the top 25, placing 22nd (19:07). The top 25 individuals received medals in the varsity race. Other area runners in the top 25 included Kindred Griffis of Newberry (8th, 18:18), Guillermo Bello of Ojibwe (18:23), Patrick McMaken (14th, 18:29), Avry Freel (16th, 18:40) and Thomas Bohn (19th, 18:58) of Cedarville; and Mitchell Satchell of Pickford (24th, 19:20). Harbor Springs had three of the top four finishers, including Jeremy Kloss, who won with a time of 16:46. Harbor Springs was the overall top girls team and also won the Small School meet title with 38 points. South Lyon won the large school girls division with 51, while Sault High finished third overall and second among Large Schools with 68. Alyssa Webber of Munising won the girls varsity race with a time of 19:51, and the Mustangs won the Class D team title with 107 points, followed by St. Ignace 212, Cedarville 220, Newberry 190, Manistique 227, Pickford 242 and Ojibwe 257. Freshman Megan Arbic led the Blue Devils, finishing second overall with a personal-best time of 19:56. Kenzie Kalchik placed 7th (20:18), Josie Roos was 15th (21:27), Rebekka Ranta 19th (21:54) and Taylor Kalchik 25 (22:41) to round out the Sault scoring. Cedarville's Emma Bohn was 5th (20:13) and Leila Schlosser was 23rd (22:22). Pickford's Heidi Hagen took 24th (22:28). The top 10 runners won medals in the junior varsity races. Katie Robinson of Sault High took 3rd in 22:07 and the Blue Devils were third in JV team scoring. Sault High won the boys JV scoring with 26 points, and Harbor Springs was second with 39. In the boys JV race, Bradley Robinson (2nd, 19:11), James Burton (3rd, 19:45), Drake Perez (5th, 19:56) and Jakob Hopkins (10th, 21:03) were top 10 finishers. In middle school racing, Harbor Springs won the combined boys-girls scoring with 18 points, just one point better than the runner-up Sault team. JKL Bahweting was third with 90, followed by St. Ignace 101, Newberry 118, Cedarville 125, St. Mary's 160, Munising 188, North Country Trails 205 and Pickford 225. Ellie Marger of the Sault won the girls 2-mile race in 12:41. Kaaleb Ranta was the top Sault finishers in the middle school boys race, taking third in 11:50. Next up for area teams will be the Straits Area Conference Jamboree 3 at the Rudyard School Farm Tuesday. By Staff reports Sault Ste. Marie Evening News - Sault Ste. Marie, MI By Staff reports
